{
  "text": "Dalton-Puffer (2011) argues that students attending CLIL programs have the same amount of content knowledge as students who follow standard curricula. Furthermore, CLIL learners are more determined students who can cope with frustrating task better hence developing a higher degree of procedural competence in the subject. Whenever they face linguistic problems, those students do not drop the task but rather tend to do intensified mental construction activity (such as elaborating and relating details, finding contradictions). As a result, the students are engaged in deeper semantic processing and can understand the concepts they are studying (Vollmer et al., 2006 cited in Dalton-Puffer, 2011: 4). In comparison to students learning in their L1, CLIL students attain the same or even higher (especially among 10-14 year old learners) cognitional development [CITATION_1] . Therefore, bilingual instruction promotes students' thinking and content learning.",
  "citation_candidates": [
